<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEARING SET ON 2 PLANS TO IMPROVE HOLLYWOOD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOSH MEYER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A public hearing on two plans dealing with the revitalization of Hollywood 
Boulevard and Hollywood's chronic traffic problems is scheduled Thursday before 
the Los Angeles Community Redevelopment Agency's Board of Commissioners. 
</P>
<P>
The hearing will start at 11 a.m. in the fourth-floor boardroom at CRA 
headquarters, 354 S. Spring St. in downtown Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
The proposed Hollywood Boulevard District Urban Design Plan and Hollywood 
Transportation Plan will become key elements in the $922-million redevelopment 
of the city's blighted movie capital, CRA officials said. 
</P>
<P>
Following the CRA hearing, the urban-design draft will be submitted to the city 
Planning Commission and City Council for review and comments before CRA 
commissioners consider its adoption. 
</P>
<P>
The transportation plan, which is expected to provide the basis for a 
transportation ordinance, also will be reviewed at City Hall, submitted to the 
CRA board for its final approval and then sent to the City Council to be 
written into law. 
</P>
<P>
Following a public review and revision process, both plans are expected to be 
ready for adoption in 1991, CRA officials said. 
</P>
<P>
Major components of the draft transportation plan include roadway improvements, 
proposals to improve traffic management and protect neighborhoods from 
increased traffic intrusion, expanded and improved public transit, reduction of 
adverse impacts from the proposed Metro Rail subway construction, and added 
parking. 
</P>
<P>
The proposed urban-design plan makes recommendations to enhance and preserve 
the architectural and functional character of the landmark boulevard. One goal 
is to encourage pedestrian use. It emphasizes residential and mixed-use 
development and contains incentives aimed at rehabilitating and reusing 
buildings of historical or architectural significance, according to the CRA. 
</P>
<P>
Copies of both plans are available for review at several locations in Hollywood 
and at CRA offices in downtown Los Angeles. A list of locations can be obtained 
by calling the CRA Hollywood site office at (213) 461-1066, or visiting the 
office at 6255 Sunset Blvd., Suite 711. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA120290-0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 316372 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 2, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
San Gabriel Valley; Part J; Page 5; Column 3 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
458 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOUNTED VOLUNTEERS PATROL ARROYO SECO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RUSSELL BEN-ALI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Every lawman needs a partner, and Don Zimmerman's is a 17-year-old buckskin 
quarter horse named Skeeter. 
</P>
<P>
Zimmerman, 78, is a member of the Pasadena Volunteer Equestrian Unit, an unpaid 
and unarmed group of riders selected by the Pasadena Police Department to 
patrol on horseback through isolated stretches of the Arroyo Seco that are 
difficult or impossible to patrol by car. 
</P>
<P>
"Basically they're reserve police, but non-sworn, who can write citations and 
are trained with Mace," said Lt. Gregg Henderson of the Pasadena Police 
Department, who, with now-retired Lt. Wesley Rice, was instrumental in getting 
police reserve status for the unit in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
In the Arroyo Seco, the unit's 16 members give warnings and citations to people 
with unleashed dogs, mountain bikers on the horse and hiking trails, and 
transients living outside the authorized camping areas. Police have caught 
drunken and disorderly visitors and even flashers after the riders radioed in 
their descriptions. 
</P>
<P>
The unit's presence alone serves to discourage activities such as 
spray-painting graffiti on rocks and trees, said Patrick Phillips, 32, a 
three-year member who patrols areas in the northern Arroyo Seco such as Oak 
Grove Park and Devil's Gate Reservoir. 
</P>
<P>
"I think our main objective is to sort of police, not so much with guns and 
clubs but with eyes and ears," Phillips said. "We're out there to create a 
presence and to try to deter any activities that would make the arroyo 
undesirable." 
</P>
<P>
Members are issued a hat, shirt, belt and saddle blanket bearing the 
blue-and-gold emblems of the Pasadena Police Department, but receive no other 
compensation. 
</P>
<P>
Each equestrian patrols the Arroyo Seco an average of 30 hours a month during 
spring and summer, when public use of the arroyo peaks. 
</P>
<P>
The unit seeks recruits who are at least 21 years old, know how to ride and 
have access to a horse, although some unit members will share their mounts, 
said Lt. Betsy Bour, the unit's highest-ranking volunteer. 
</P>
<P>
Applicants should call the administrative section of the Pasadena Police 
Department. They must complete an interview and submit to a thorough background 
check. 
</P>
<P>
Horses must also prove that they are qualified for the work. "Some horses just 
don't do well on the trail at all," Bour said. "Some horses have done only ring 
work, and out on the trail every blowing branch scares them." 
</P>
<P>
Human members of the unit say the patrols give them a lot of satisfaction. 
</P>
<P>
"I enjoy riding with the group. It's good exercise," said Zimmerman, a retired 
tool-and-die maker from San Gabriel. "And you feel like you're providing a 
service to the community, (and) at the same time enjoying it. . . . Most of the 
people are glad to see us coming. They appreciate us being there." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Don Zimmerman, 78, of San Gabriel and his horse, Skeeter, on patrol 
recently with the 16-member Pasadena Volunteer Equestrian Unit. KAREN TAPIA / 
Los Angeles Times; Photo, Most of the unit's horses are kept at San Pasqual 
Stables in Pasadena. Horses, like riders, must prove they can negotiate arroyo 
trails. ; Photo, NOT HORSING AROUND: The 16 members of the Pasadena Volunteer 
Equestrian Unit patrol the Arroyo Seco, maneuvering into rugged places that 
police cars can't reach. Above, Don Zimmerman prepares to mount his horse. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
