<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 14; Column 3; Foreign Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
192 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAUDIS VOW TO TAKE FIRST BLOW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
EASTERN SAUDI ARABIA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This nation's military will take the first losses among the multinational 
forces opposing Iraq if war breaks out, the Saudi joint commanding general said 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
"We believe that if our friends are here to shed their blood for us, the least 
we can do is to put my forces right in front," Prince Khalid ibn Sultan, a 
nephew of King Fahd, told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
"And if there is any bloodshed, I can assure you Saudis will take it before 
their friends." 
</P>
<P>
The prince, who shares authority over the multinational force in Saudi Arabia 
with the U.S. commander, Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf, declined to speculate on 
whether Washington's offer to talk to Iraq represents a "last chance" to avoid 
war. 
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Prince Khalid told several hundred Saudi marines and seamen at a 
Persian Gulf naval base that the United Nations had given Saddam Hussein a 
chance to leave Kuwait without war. 
</P>
<P>
"We hope this problem will be solved with peaceful means, using our brains," he 
said. "We hope President Saddam (Hussein) will come to his senses -- we don't 
want to go to war," said the prince, who received his military education in 
Britain and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
