<HEADLINE>
<P>
FRAZIER GETS 6-MONTH BAN FOR WEIGHT INFRACTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL CHRISTINE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ricky Frazier, the jockey whose victory aboard Allijeba was erased because of a 
weight discrepancy after a $250,000 race at Bay Meadows on Oct. 14, has been 
suspended for six months, the stewards at the San Mateo track announced 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
The suspension, which started Saturday, runs through May 31. 
</P>
<P>
Frazier is currently riding at the Fair Grounds, and stewards at the New 
Orleans track, following racing custom, took the jockey off his mounts there 
Saturday. Racing has an informal reciprocity rule that prohibits jockeys from 
competing anywhere while under suspension. 
</P>
<P>
Fair Grounds sources indicated that Frazier would appeal the suspension to the 
California Horse Racing Board, but the jockey couldn't be reached for comment. 
Six months is considered to be a severe penalty, but the stewards are believed 
to have considered Frazier's previous record, which includes two fines of $100 
each for weight violations. 
</P>
<P>
Allijeba was supposed to carry 126 pounds in the Final Fourteen Stakes at Bay 
Meadows. When Frazier returned to the scales after a nose victory over Tex's 
Zing, the weight was 123 pounds. BILL CHRISTINE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
FRAZIER, RICKY; JOCKEYS; SUSPENSIONS; SPORTS RULES AND REGULATIONS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA120290-0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 316692 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 2, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
